File: src/app/dom-builders.ts:585-591 (makeIcon)
Title: Decorative Bootstrap-Icons <i> glyphs are not hidden from assistive tech

Finding:
Every icon added in this changeset — the in-input search glyph, the clear button's `bi-x-lg`, the close button's `bi-x-lg`, the spinner's `bi-arrow-repeat`, and all the menu-item glyphs produced by `makeIcon` ('upload', 'download', 'trash', 'arrows-move', 'files', 'folder-plus') — are `<i>` elements with no `aria-hidden`. Bootstrap Icons render their glyph via a CSS `::before { content: '\f...' }` rule, and some screen readers announce generated content / private-use-area code points as stray noise. Because each icon is paired with a visible text label (or, for the clear/close buttons, an `aria-label`), the icon is purely decorative and must be hidden from AT per WCAG 1.3.1. The central fix is in `makeIcon` (covers all menu-item icons); the few icons created inline in app.ts and render-orchestrator.ts must be patched separately.

Fix instructions (follow exactly; make targeted, minimal changes):
In src/app/dom-builders.ts, in the `makeIcon(name)` function, before returning the element add `icon.setAttribute('aria-hidden', 'true');`. Then in src/app.ts set the same attribute on `searchIcon` (the `bi bi-search search-icon` element) and on `clearIcon` (the `bi bi-x-lg` inside the clear button) right after each is created; also set it on `closeIcon` (the dialog close button's `bi bi-x-lg`). In src/app/render-orchestrator.ts set `aria-hidden='true'` on the spinner icon (`spinnerIcon`, class `bi bi-arrow-repeat spinning`). Run the existing dom-builders / start-app / render-orchestration tests; none should assert the absence of aria-hidden, but if a snapshot-like assertion fails, update it.

